attributes.magic: ELF 32-bit MSB executable, MIPS, MIPS-I version 1 (SYSV), statically linked, stripped

threat_severity.level_description: Severity MEDIUM because it was considered trojan.

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: MIPS-based DDoS botnet, likely a variant of the Mirai or Gafgyt (Bashlite) family. The binary exhibits several classic malicious behaviors: it implements multiple attack vectors (SYN, ACK, UDP, HTTP, ICMP, and GRE floods) as evidenced by C2 commands like '!syn', '!udpcustom', and '!http'; it includes anti-VM logic by checking '/sys/class/dmi/id/product_name' for 'VMware'; it ensures single-instance execution via a lock file '/tmp/.bot_lock'; and it contains a process scanner in sub_4026e4 that iterates through '/proc' to identify and terminate competing malware (searching for strings like 'wget', 'curl', 'tftp') or system utilities. Network communication utilizes raw sockets and hardcoded User-Agents to spoof legitimate web traffic.
